article.description:
Lisa Leslie scored 17 points to become the
first 4,000-point scorer in WNBA history, and Mwadi Mabika scored all seven of her team's points in the second overtime to give the Los Angeles Sparks an 85-80 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on
Thursday
article.headline: Leslie first 4,000-point scorer in history
article.story:
SACRAMENTO (AP) -- Lisa Leslie is making the WNBA record book
look like her personal resume.

Leslie, the league's first 3,000-point scorer, became the first
to reach 4,000 points on Thursday, and teammate Mwadi Mabika scored
seven in the second overtime to give the Los Angeles Sparks an
85-80 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on Thursday night.

Leslie surpassed the milestone on a fallaway jumper in the lane
with 13:26 left in the first half. She finished with 17 points.

"It's a great feeling to accomplish that," Leslie said. "But
I don't know what it means totally because I am one of the pioneers
in the league. Still, it's great to be first."

Leslie also tops the WNBA in career rebounds with 2,208 after 12
more on Thursday, and is second in blocked shots.

Mabika scored 24 points to lead the Sparks (18-7), who have won
four straight, and 11 of 12. She missed 20 of 28 shots, but
personally outscored the Monarchs 7-2 in the second overtime.

"I was tired, everyone was tired," said Mabika. "My shots
weren't falling, but I just took what they gave me in overtime."

In the first overtime, Sacramento forward DeMya Walker tied the
score at 78 on a drive with 44 seconds left. She had a chance to
end it in the final seconds, but her off-balance shot didn't fall.

With the Monarchs trailing 68-63 with 29 seconds left in
regulation, Kara Lawson made two 3-pointers -- the second with 4.2
seconds left -- to send the game to overtime.

"We have been so close to being .500 and we wanted to get there
before the break," Lawson said. "We need to be above .500 to make
the playoffs. ... It's a very frustrating loss."

Trailing by as many as 14 points in the second half, the
Monarchs (11-13) rallied behind the inside play of Walker and
rookie Rebekkah Brunson. A fast-break layup by Brunson concluded a
16-3 run that put the Monarchs ahead 60-58 with 3:35 left.

"They work hard, that's what Sacramento does," Sparks coach
Karleen Thompson said. "They have three big bodies down low and
they crash the boards. They are aggressive; when we play them we
know we have to take it up a step."

Lawson led five Monarchs in double figures with 20 points,
including six 3-pointers. Walker added 16 points, eight rebounds
and five assists. Yolanda Griffith had 13 points and a season-high
16 rebounds, while Ruthie Bolton had 13 points and Tangela Smith
scored 12.

Nikki Teasley had 19 points and Temecka Dixon scored 11 for the
first-place Sparks.
